1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:07,120
Renko charts can be your biggest edge in scalping 
or day trading, if you know the right strategy! 

2
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:13,040
Well, this trading guide rewrites the rules, 
giving you the ultimate Renko strategy to  

3
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:18,400
dominate any market.
 
Renko charts present  

4
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:24,800
a distinctive way of plotting price movement.
Instead of using time-based candles, they rely  

5
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:31,840
on discrete price increments, forming bricks. 
 
This process strips away a good deal of noise,  

6
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:38,560
since each Renko brick forms only after 
price has moved a set amount up or down. 

7
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:45,680
You will very soon find that Renko charts 
highlight trends and consolidations more clearly. 

8
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:51,440
To illustrate, imagine you decide 
on a brick size of $1 per brick. 

9
00:00:51,440 --> 00:00:57,520
If the market is steadily climbing, each 
time the price advances $1 beyond the most  

10
00:00:57,520 --> 00:01:03,920
recent completed brick, a new brick prints.
If the price fails to move in that increment,  

11
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:07,520
no new brick appears.
This helps you identify  

12
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:12,640
well-defined waves in the market.
 
On a regular candlestick chart,  

13
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:20,000
each bar prints at fixed intervals (like every 
five minutes), even if price is relatively flat. 

14
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:26,000
With Renko charts, nothing updates unless the 
market accomplishes a full brick’s worth of  

15
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:32,160
movement. This means that in an extremely 
thin or sideways market, you might see a  

16
00:01:32,160 --> 00:01:40,560
slow pace of brick formation, whereas in a highly 
volatile environment, the chart can move rapidly.
  

17
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:46,960
Renko method accentuates straightforward 
patterns like higher highs or lower lows. 

18
00:01:46,960 --> 00:01:53,360
A series of consecutive bricks of the same 
color (and direction) clearly reveals patterns  

19
00:01:53,360 --> 00:02:00,000
of momentum, while color flips serve as 
direct signals of a potential reversal. 
  

20
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,200
Because each brick has the same size, 
a cluster of bricks all pointing in the  

21
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:11,040
same direction can reflect a robust trend.
Any deviation from this pattern can be a  

22
00:02:11,040 --> 00:02:17,760
cautionary sign that momentum is changing.
 
Renko’s fundamental purpose is to simplify. 

23
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:24,560
Instead of drawing a candle every X minutes, 
you see a brick only if price justifies it. 

24
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:28,160
That can be helpful for those 
who want to identify direction  

25
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:34,880
quickly or who prefer mechanical systems.
 
Of course, some nuance remains. If brick size  

26
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:41,360
is set too small, you might get a choppy chart 
that prints bricks on minimal fluctuations. 

27
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:46,582
If it’s set too large, you might fail to 
capture subtle intraday turning points. 

28
00:02:46,582 --> 00:02:46,677
Thus, picking a suitable brick size is crucial. 
That’s a key principle we’ll explore later.

29
00:02:46,677 --> 00:02:46,837
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
CHAPTER 2 – ADVANTAGES AND LIMITATIONS 

30
00:02:46,837 --> 00:02:50,160
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 
 
Renko charts offer several unique advantages  

31
00:02:50,160 --> 00:02:54,160
for reading market direction.
One of the primary benefits is  

32
00:02:54,160 --> 00:03:00,880
the filtering of minor market fluctuations.
A standard time-based chart often shows you  

33
00:03:00,880 --> 00:03:07,360
every tick or bar, leading to “noise” that can 
affect your interpretation of price movement. 

34
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:13,840
By contrast, Renko bricks appear only if 
the market moves beyond a certain threshold,  

35
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:20,320
effectively smoothing out small, random wiggles 
that do not add meaningful information. 
  

36
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:25,680
This smoothing effect can be invaluable 
when attempting to see the overall trend. 

37
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:32,240
For instance, if you are scanning for a consistent 
uptrend, a Renko chart can reveal it through a  

38
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:39,760
stacked run of green or upward-pointing bricks.
 
Another key advantage rests in how well Renko  

39
00:03:39,760 --> 00:03:45,840
illustrates clear support and resistance zones.
Because the chart does not print new bricks for  

40
00:03:45,840 --> 00:03:50,880
every price tick, it often forms 
distinct patterns, where price has  

41
00:03:50,880 --> 00:03:56,640
trouble rising above or dipping below.
Suppose you see a region where multiple  

42
00:03:56,640 --> 00:04:02,640
bricks top out at roughly the same level, 
forming an obvious horizontal boundary. 

43
00:04:02,640 --> 00:04:08,960
You might interpret that boundary as a robust 
area of supply or resistance, where sellers have  

44
00:04:08,960 --> 00:04:14,320
repeatedly stopped further upside attempts. 
 
Also, you may also see zones where several  

45
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:19,680
bricks bounced near the same price, 
signifying strong support or demand. 

46
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:25,680
Once again, the Renko process of printing 
bricks only on significant moves can make  

47
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:30,400
these levels more apparent than on 
a traditional candlestick chart.
  

48
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:37,280
However, there are limitations. One major 
caution is that the “timeless” structure means  

49
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:43,840
you cannot see how long a move took to develop.
Rapid fluctuations might produce multiple bricks  

50
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:51,360
in a short time, while a slow, meandering market 
might barely print any new bricks for hours. 
  

51
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:56,320
Also, selecting the wrong brick 
size can undermine Renko’s benefits. 

52
00:04:56,320 --> 00:04:59,920
If your brick size is set 
too small in a choppy market,  

53
00:04:59,920 --> 00:05:04,880
you can get frequent flips in brick 
color, generating false signals. 

54
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:11,120
If your brick size is too big, important moves 
may remain hidden behind the large threshold. 
  

55
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:17,760
Thus, calibration is crucial, taking into account 
average true range, typical daily price movement,  

56
00:05:17,760 --> 00:05:22,000
or your personal style.
For day trading and scalping,  

57
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:27,120
you might might select a very small 
brick size to capture intraday swings. 

58
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:33,880
A swing trader looking at multi-day moves may 
pick a larger brick size for a wider lens.

59
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:34,038
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
CHAPTER 3 – RENKO CHART CONSTRUCTION 

60
00:05:34,038 --> 00:05:36,880
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 
To trade using Renko, you first must  

61
00:05:36,880 --> 00:05:40,052
understand how these charts are constructed.
By default, many charting programs let you  

62
00:05:40,052 --> 00:05:42,000
specify a fixed brick size.
Suppose you set 10 pips for  

63
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
a currency pair or 1$ for a stock.
That means a new “up” brick draws  

64
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:53,760
if the price climbs 10 pips (or $1) 
above the previous brick’s high.
  

65
00:05:53,760 --> 00:06:00,320
A “down” brick forms if it declines that 
same threshold below the prior brick’s low. 

66
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:06,160
Because the threshold is absolute, you ignore 
time-based intervals such as 5-minute or daily  

67
00:06:06,160 --> 00:06:13,280
bars, focusing purely on price increments. 
 
Most platforms automate all these mechanics,  

68
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:18,800
so your main choice is the brick size.
Some traders prefer a fixed size. 

69
00:06:18,800 --> 00:06:24,640
For example, for a stock that 
usually moves $1 to $2 intraday,  

70
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:31,200
you might pick a $0.10 or $0.20 brick.
For a currency pair, you might choose 5  

71
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:38,160
or 10 pips, depending on typical volatility. 
 
Again, if you pick an excessively small setting  

72
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:43,440
and the market is jumpy, you will see 
bricks flipping up and down constantly,  

73
00:06:43,440 --> 00:06:48,240
which defeats the smoothing advantage.
If your brick size is too large,  

74
00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:54,720
you risk losing detail in your analysis 
 
A widely adopted Renko approach is to use  

75
00:06:54,720 --> 00:07:01,680
Average True Range for determining brick size.
ATR is a measure of volatility, typically  

76
00:07:01,680 --> 00:07:07,120
taking an average of recent true ranges 
(the difference between high and low). 

77
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:11,040
By tying brick size to the 
market’s current volatility,  

78
00:07:11,040 --> 00:07:16,720
you allow the chart to adapt dynamically. 
 
For instance, if a currency pair becomes  

79
00:07:16,720 --> 00:07:23,840
more volatile, your ATR-based brick size 
might increase, so it still filters out  

80
00:07:23,840 --> 00:07:30,880
small random movements, but captures the newly 
expanded price fluctuations more systematically. 

81
00:07:30,880 --> 00:07:37,680
In a quiet environment, brick size shrinks so 
that you do not end up with a motionless chart. 
  

82
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:43,360
This approach can be more stable, as the 
brick size adjusts to new conditions. 

83
00:07:43,360 --> 00:07:49,120
A purely fixed size might be workable 
for day trading, but if that instrument’s  

84
00:07:49,120 --> 00:07:54,800
volatility changes drastically, you 
might have to keep manually adjusting.
  

85
00:07:54,800 --> 00:08:00,240
When adopting an ATR-based approach, 
you also have to accept that the renko  

86
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:06,960
chart might shift as ATR changes.
That is, if ATR was 10 pips for a  

87
00:08:06,960 --> 00:08:12,800
currency pair last week, but then rose 
to 15 pips this week, your new bricks  

88
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:17,440
might appear somewhat differently.
 
Now, you could also choose to see  

89
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:21,840
the wicks on Renko charts.
Wicks appear as thin lines  

90
00:08:21,840 --> 00:08:26,400
above or below each brick.
These small lines might reveal  

91
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:31,760
sudden pushes or quick rejections 
during the formation of each brick.
  

92
00:08:31,760 --> 00:08:38,080
Some prefer clean bricks without wicks, 
because they want to remove all small noise. 

93
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:43,280
Others want to see every flicker of 
price, believing that wicks hold big  

94
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:48,880
clues about supply or demand shifts.
A wick can mark a moment when buyers  

95
00:08:48,880 --> 00:08:53,680
or sellers took charge for a 
short span, then lost their grip. 

96
00:08:53,680 --> 00:08:57,840
That is why wicks can show 
dominance on a smaller time scale.

97
00:08:57,840 --> 00:08:58,200
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
CHAPTER 4 – PRICE ACTION STRATEGIES 

98
00:08:58,200 --> 00:09:01,440
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 
Renko charts resonate strongly with price  

99
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:08,000
action traders who want to focus on raw movement.
One fundamental technique is to look for a series  

100
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:14,080
of consecutive bricks of the same color, 
which can signal a trending condition. 

101
00:09:14,080 --> 00:09:19,680
For example, if you see four or five green 
bricks in a row with no interruption,  

102
00:09:19,680 --> 00:09:26,080
that might reflect a strong bullish push.
If you identify a well-defined uptrend, you can  

103
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:32,800
look to buy on small pullbacks, anticipating 
that the primary direction will continue.
  

104
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:39,200
Another method is identifying breakout points.
Because Renko charts clarify support and  

105
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:44,640
resistance, you might mark horizontal 
lines where price repeatedly failed  

106
00:09:44,640 --> 00:09:49,680
to surpass a certain brick level.
Suppose you spot a zone where multiple  

107
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:56,320
bricks reversed to the downside around the same 
price area. On a candlestick chart, that might  

108
00:09:56,320 --> 00:10:02,720
have been a choppy region, but on Renko, it 
looks like a distinct “ceiling” of bricks. 

109
00:10:02,720 --> 00:10:07,360
If the price eventually breaks above 
that ceiling, you interpret it as a  

110
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:13,920
breakout with less noise to distract you. 
 
Additionally, some price action traders watch  

111
00:10:13,920 --> 00:10:20,880
for color flips to identify potential reversals.
If you have a streak of red bricks forming a  

112
00:10:20,880 --> 00:10:26,800
downtrend, and then you see the creation of 
a green brick that might be an early sign the  

113
00:10:26,800 --> 00:10:32,800
market is flipping bullish on the short term.
If you prefer more confirmation, you could  

114
00:10:32,800 --> 00:10:37,200
wait for two or three consecutive 
bricks of the opposite color. 

115
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:42,160
The beauty of Renko is that each 
brick is uniform in size; thus,  

116
00:10:42,160 --> 00:10:48,960
a color shift literally indicates that price 
has moved enough to overcome that threshold. 
  

117
00:10:48,960 --> 00:10:53,600
Another valuable dimension is 
analyzing sideways conditions. 

118
00:10:53,600 --> 00:10:59,600
Sometimes the market stalls, creating an 
alternating pattern of up and down bricks,  

119
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:06,160
but staying within a certain horizontal band.
You might identify a “box” or “range” by  

120
00:11:06,160 --> 00:11:11,680
marking the highest up-brick and the 
lowest down-brick within that region. 

121
00:11:11,680 --> 00:11:17,280
If the price fails to exit that box for 
a while, it indicates a consolidation. 
  

122
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:24,080
A Renko trader might either skip trading that 
range if it is too narrow or might attempt to  

123
00:11:24,080 --> 00:11:31,520
fade each side (selling at the top of the band or 
buying at the bottom), hoping the range persists. 

124
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:38,960
Then, if price ultimately breaks out of that box, 
you can quickly pivot into a trending strategy.
  

125
00:11:38,960 --> 00:11:42,720
One essential concept is 
the notion of pivot bricks. 

126
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:47,440
You can observe that after a run of 
consecutive bricks, the chart forms  

127
00:11:47,440 --> 00:11:54,400
a single or double brick in the opposite 
color, then resumes the original direction. 

128
00:11:54,400 --> 00:11:59,360
That small counter move can be a 
“pullback” in price action terms. 

129
00:11:59,360 --> 00:12:05,280
Many traders look to buy near the pivot 
brick if the overall direction is bullish,  

130
00:12:05,280 --> 00:12:10,400
with a stop just below the last low. 
 
This approach effectively tries to  

131
00:12:10,400 --> 00:12:15,200
catch the resumption of the trend 
before it fully re-accelerates. 

132
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:19,600
Of course, you might see a deeper 
correction of multiple bricks,  

133
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:22,560
indicating a stronger shift in momentum.

134
00:12:22,560 --> 00:12:22,927
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
CHAPTER 5 – INCORPORATING BASIC INDICATORS 

135
00:12:22,927 --> 00:12:26,240
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 
While many traders prefer a purely price action  

136
00:12:26,240 --> 00:12:33,600
approach, others enjoy combining Renko with one 
or two basic overlays, such as moving averages. 

137
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:39,840
Because Renko is a “price-distilled” chart, 
certain indicators might behave differently.
  

138
00:12:39,840 --> 00:12:44,800
For example, a 20-period moving 
average on a Renko chart is not  

139
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:50,560
measuring the last 20 bars in time, 
but rather the last 20 bricks formed. 

140
00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:55,760
That means if the market was quiet and 
formed few bricks, the moving average  

141
00:12:55,760 --> 00:13:02,640
might not update frequently; if the market was 
volatile, the average shifts more rapidly. 
  

142
00:13:02,640 --> 00:13:09,200
One of the simplest uses is to add a single moving 
average, say a 50-brick one, to observe whether  

143
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:14,480
the price is above or below that line.
If the bricks remain stacked above the  

144
00:13:14,480 --> 00:13:18,960
line for multiple bricks, it 
suggests a bullish environment. 

145
00:13:18,960 --> 00:13:25,520
If they cross decisively below the moving average, 
it hints that momentum is turning bearish.
  

146
00:13:25,520 --> 00:13:29,520
Renko makes these crossovers 
potentially more significant,  

147
00:13:29,520 --> 00:13:36,000
because each brick must move a set distance.
On a typical chart, price might briefly poke below  

148
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:42,720
a moving average, only to revert in the same bar.
On Renko, crossing that line typically means the  

149
00:13:42,720 --> 00:13:49,280
price overcame a threshold of movement—some 
may see that as a more conclusive sign.
  

150
00:13:49,280 --> 00:13:55,440
Additionally, some traders apply an 
oscillator, like RSI on the Renko chart. 

151
00:13:55,440 --> 00:14:00,400
The logic is that although time is less 
relevant, you can still check if the market  

152
00:14:00,400 --> 00:14:07,040
has momentum or not. Then you watch for a 
color flip or a break of a certain pivot. 

153
00:14:07,040 --> 00:14:11,840
This might refine your timing. 
 
You could, for instance, short when bricks  

154
00:14:11,840 --> 00:14:19,040
turn red right as RSI is below its 50-level.
Still, be aware that these indicators  

155
00:14:19,040 --> 00:14:25,146
might not behave the same as on time-based 
charts, since they measure the last bricks.

156
00:14:25,146 --> 00:14:25,318
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
CHAPTER 6 – MULTI-TIMEFRAME AND CROSS-VERIFICATION 

157
00:14:25,318 --> 00:14:28,000
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 
Although Renko is distinct from time-based  

158
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:33,440
charts, many traders find synergy 
in analyzing multiple perspectives. 

159
00:14:33,440 --> 00:14:40,240
For instance, you might open a 4-hour candlestick 
chart (or daily chart for bigger swings), to  

160
00:14:40,240 --> 00:14:45,520
identify key support or resistance 
or major trends, then zoom into a  

161
00:14:45,520 --> 00:14:50,480
Renko chart for precise entries. 
 
The higher timeframe guides your  

162
00:14:50,480 --> 00:14:55,840
direction bias—maybe you see that the 
daily chart is forming higher highs,  

163
00:14:55,840 --> 00:15:01,200
indicating an uptrend—so you only take 
“bullish” bricks on the Renko chart. 

164
00:15:01,200 --> 00:15:05,120
This alignment helps you avoid 
fighting the bigger picture.
  

165
00:15:05,120 --> 00:15:09,840
Some traders do the entire analysis 
in Renko. You could, for instance,  

166
00:15:09,840 --> 00:15:15,840
use a “large brick” Renko chart to see the 
bigger directional context, then switch to a  

167
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:21,760
smaller-brick chart to fine-tune your entry.
On the large-brick chart, you see fewer  

168
00:15:21,760 --> 00:15:27,200
but bolder swings, which might counsel 
that the market is overall bullish. 

169
00:15:27,200 --> 00:15:34,080
Then, on the smaller-brick chart, you watch for 
a minor dip of 2 or 3 bricks as your entry. 
  

170
00:15:34,080 --> 00:15:37,840
Cross-verifying signals 
can reduce false positives. 

171
00:15:37,840 --> 00:15:43,760
For example, if your big-brick Renko chart 
has not reversed color but your small-brick  

172
00:15:43,760 --> 00:15:49,600
chart indicates a short signal, you might 
pass, suspecting it is a micro pullback  

173
00:15:49,600 --> 00:15:55,760
that will soon revert to the major uptrend.
The same logic applies if your daily candlestick  

174
00:15:55,760 --> 00:16:01,280
chart shows a strong bullish technical 
pattern (like a breakout of a range),  

175
00:16:01,280 --> 00:16:07,120
but your Renko intraday chart is unclear.
You might wait until the Renko chart  

176
00:16:07,120 --> 00:16:12,214
lines up with the overall bullish 
story, thus confirming alignment.

177
00:16:12,214 --> 00:16:12,358
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
CHAPTER 7 – STRATEGIES 

178
00:16:12,358 --> 00:16:15,280
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 
Now let’s talk strategies. Price action  

179
00:16:15,280 --> 00:16:20,240
is the first method to study here.
Renko pairs well with price action  

180
00:16:20,240 --> 00:16:26,960
because each brick cuts out minor wicks.
You see true direction with fewer fake signals.  

181
00:16:26,960 --> 00:16:34,160
On renko, watch how bricks form and flip color.
A series of green bricks can mean an uptrend. 

182
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:38,640
A quick shift to red bricks can 
mean a short term reversal. 
  

183
00:16:38,640 --> 00:16:44,160
Look for patterns in the bricks. Sometimes 
you see triple tops or double bottoms. 

184
00:16:44,160 --> 00:16:48,640
They form a stair-step shape on renko.
These patterns can guide you  

185
00:16:48,640 --> 00:16:52,640
on possible breakouts. 
 
A triple top might show the  

186
00:16:52,640 --> 00:16:58,720
price failing three times at a certain level.
If you see a new brick above that level,  

187
00:16:58,720 --> 00:17:02,240
it might confirm an upward break.
The same logic applies  

188
00:17:02,240 --> 00:17:08,720
to double or triple bottoms.
 
Another approach is to watch pin-like bricks. On  

189
00:17:08,720 --> 00:17:15,920
standard candle charts, you might see a pin bar.
On renko, that becomes a sudden shift in bricks. 

190
00:17:15,920 --> 00:17:22,480
If you see a single brick that forms a quick 
pivot, it might point to a strong bounce. 
  

191
00:17:22,480 --> 00:17:27,440
Supply and demand is next. These 
zones reflect areas where buyers  

192
00:17:27,440 --> 00:17:32,480
or sellers took over in the past.
On a renko chart, these zones can  

193
00:17:32,480 --> 00:17:36,160
appear as brick clusters.
If you see a strong set of  

194
00:17:36,160 --> 00:17:42,400
bricks that moved up from a level, that 
zone might act as a new support later. 

195
00:17:42,400 --> 00:17:47,920
If you see a fast drop from a high band, 
that region might pose resistance. 
  

196
00:17:47,920 --> 00:17:54,560
Draw these zones on your chart. Wait for price to 
approach them again. Watch how bricks react there. 

197
00:17:54,560 --> 00:18:00,320
If bricks stall or flip at an old 
zone, that can tell you the next path. 

198
00:18:00,320 --> 00:18:04,560
Sometimes you see a cluster of 
bricks turning red at a supply  

199
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:10,960
zone. That might show renewed selling.
 
Price often stalls near these zones. When  

200
00:18:10,960 --> 00:18:15,040
renko bricks print sideways, 
that can mean a base forming. 

201
00:18:15,040 --> 00:18:20,800
If those sideways bricks occur near a known 
supply or demand band, you watch for an eventual  

202
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:27,600
breakout. Some traders like to see a strong 
color flip at these bands to confirm direction. 

203
00:18:27,600 --> 00:18:32,400
Others wait for a retest.
 
Moving averages can fit renko well,  

204
00:18:32,400 --> 00:18:36,960
as can help confirm the trend.
If bricks stay above the average,  

205
00:18:36,960 --> 00:18:42,160
that can show an uptrend.
If bricks stay below, it can show a downtrend.
  

206
00:18:42,160 --> 00:18:45,680
Price action plus a moving 
average can work smoothly. 

207
00:18:45,680 --> 00:18:48,880
Watch for bricks to align 
with the average’s slope. 

208
00:18:48,880 --> 00:18:54,080
If the average points up and bricks 
stay green, you might hold a long bias. 

209
00:18:54,080 --> 00:18:59,040
If the average flattens and bricks keep 
flipping color, you might stay out. 
  

210
00:18:59,040 --> 00:19:04,480
Another strategy is a breakout approach. 
Wait for a period of sideways bricks. 

211
00:19:04,480 --> 00:19:11,120
Then watch for that new brick that closes beyond 
the range. If you see a multi-brick consolidation,  

212
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:17,600
a breakout brick can indicate a bigger wave.
For instance, if bricks move sideways around  

213
00:19:17,600 --> 00:19:21,920
a specific level, then a green 
brick closes above that zone,  

214
00:19:21,920 --> 00:19:26,960
that signals potential bullish momentum. 
 
Confirm with your moving average  

215
00:19:26,960 --> 00:19:32,160
or an extra filter if you like.
That filter could be a supply zone  

216
00:19:32,160 --> 00:19:38,960
overhead. If you see no major supply zone 
close by, the breakout might run further.
  

217
00:19:38,960 --> 00:19:44,800
Another approach is a pullback strategy. Price 
rarely runs straight up or straight down. 

218
00:19:44,800 --> 00:19:50,880
Even in an uptrend, there are dips. On 
renko, watch for a series of green bricks. 

219
00:19:50,880 --> 00:19:56,000
Then watch for one or two red bricks 
forming. That might be a pullback. 

220
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:02,480
If you see the next green brick near a key 
area, that can be your cue to go long again. 

221
00:20:02,480 --> 00:20:08,800
You can base that on a demand zone. Or you might 
use the moving average to find a bounce area. 

222
00:20:08,800 --> 00:20:14,720
When you see a green brick appear again, it 
might confirm that the uptrend still holds.
  

223
00:20:14,720 --> 00:20:18,080
Supply-demand flips also shape a strategy. 

224
00:20:18,080 --> 00:20:23,120
Mark your supply zone overhead. 
Mark your demand zone below. 

225
00:20:23,120 --> 00:20:29,600
If bricks reach the supply zone and flip from 
green to red, that might be a short signal. 

226
00:20:29,600 --> 00:20:36,560
If bricks drop to a demand zone and flip from 
red to green, that might be a long signal. 

227
00:20:36,560 --> 00:20:40,400
Some traders set an entry 
one brick beyond the flip. 

228
00:20:40,400 --> 00:20:44,800
Others wait for two bricks to 
confirm. Each approach is valid,  

229
00:20:44,800 --> 00:20:51,280
but test it on past charts first.
 
Candlestick patterns can be adapted to renko. 

230
00:20:51,280 --> 00:20:55,840
You do not see wicks in the same 
way, but you see shifts in color. 

231
00:20:55,840 --> 00:21:01,440
Pay attention to quick flips. That might 
mimic a bullish or bearish a pin bar. 
  

232
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:05,680
If you see one color brick quickly 
replaced by the other color brick,  

233
00:21:05,680 --> 00:21:11,600
with a wick, that can be a signal.
If that occurs near a supply or demand zone, it  

234
00:21:11,600 --> 00:21:17,680
gains weight and it may show a bigger reversal.
 
The length of any wick is key. 

235
00:21:17,680 --> 00:21:23,520
A long upper wick might reflect strong 
selling pressure from a zone of resistance. 

236
00:21:23,520 --> 00:21:29,360
A long lower wick can hint that 
buyers stepped in at a support layer. 

237
00:21:29,360 --> 00:21:35,200
The longer the wick, the bigger the rejection. 
 
If you see a big wick, that can mean that price  

238
00:21:35,200 --> 00:21:42,240
tried to move strongly but got forced back.
That might mark a zone of heavy supply or demand. 

239
00:21:42,240 --> 00:21:48,080
If you see a tiny wick, that might be 
a small hesitation, not a major shift. 

240
00:21:48,080 --> 00:21:53,680
No wicks can reflect a clean, forceful 
run. Meaning strong momentum.
  

241
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:57,680
Many traders keep a note of 
lines of support and resistance. 

242
00:21:57,680 --> 00:22:04,000
In a normal candlestick chart, you draw 
horizontal lines at swing highs or lows. 

243
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:07,840
With renko, you do the same, 
but it can look steadier. 

244
00:22:07,840 --> 00:22:13,280
If you see repeated attempts to break a 
horizontal level around the same brick level,  

245
00:22:13,280 --> 00:22:19,280
that forms a line. Wait for a decisive move 
beyond that line to consider a trade. 
  

246
00:22:19,280 --> 00:22:25,760
Pair that with the shape of renko bricks.
Are bricks flipping color at that exact area? 

247
00:22:25,760 --> 00:22:30,160
That detail might confirm a 
breakout or a false break. 

248
00:22:30,160 --> 00:22:35,440
A false break might show a single brick 
that tries to push beyond the line,  

249
00:22:35,440 --> 00:22:42,320
but the next brick forms back in the old range.
 
Another strategy involves pivot points. I  

250
00:22:42,320 --> 00:22:49,280
personally never trade without pivot levels.
I monitor the daily or weekly pivot lines. 

251
00:22:49,280 --> 00:22:52,880
Then I look to see if the 
bricks respect those lines. 

252
00:22:52,880 --> 00:22:59,200
If bricks hover near an “R1” pivot, you 
might wait for a color flip for a short. 

253
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:04,400
If bricks push above main pivot, 
I might hold a bullish view. 
  

254
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:10,960
Stop-loss placement can be simpler with renko. You 
can place a stop a few bricks behind your entry. 

255
00:23:10,960 --> 00:23:16,960
If you go long on a green brick that forms 
above resistance, you might tuck your stop  

256
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:21,120
behind the last red brick.
Because renko bricks filter  

257
00:23:21,120 --> 00:23:28,000
small spikes, your stop might be tighter. 
 
This is a technical approach, not psychological. 

258
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:34,400
You can also trail your stop by a certain 
number of bricks as price moves in your favor. 

259
00:23:34,400 --> 00:23:38,640
Some traders like to wait 
for a color change to exit. 
  

260
00:23:38,640 --> 00:23:44,240
Other strategies might involve divergences.
If you use an oscillator, watch for a  

261
00:23:44,240 --> 00:23:50,320
discrepancy between price and your indicator.
If bricks make new highs but the indicator  

262
00:23:50,320 --> 00:23:56,320
does not, that can show momentum loss.
You might see a color flip soon. This is  

263
00:23:56,320 --> 00:24:02,800
more advanced, but it’s definitely worth it
 
Now, at first, practice on historical charts.  

264
00:24:02,800 --> 00:24:08,080
Mark each zone where price turned.
Mark each breakout. Watch how  

265
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:13,520
many bricks form before a big run.
See if moving average crosses help. 

266
00:24:13,520 --> 00:24:17,280
Tweak your brick size if you 
get too many false flips. 

267
00:24:17,280 --> 00:24:22,640
Check if your approach works best with 
a trending pair or a more volatile one. 

268
00:24:22,640 --> 00:24:26,320
And always know that signals must have context. 

269
00:24:26,320 --> 00:24:33,120
That context is the bigger trend, the 
supply-demand layout, and recent highs or lows.
  

270
00:24:33,120 --> 00:24:38,960
Area-based strategies also fit. Mark 
an area where price consolidated. 

271
00:24:38,960 --> 00:24:43,280
Then wait for either a breakout 
or a bounce from that range. 

272
00:24:43,280 --> 00:24:50,080
If bricks break the top side, you might go 
long. If bricks form below, you might short. 
  

273
00:24:50,080 --> 00:24:55,040
This is standard price action, 
but renko can make it more direct. 

274
00:24:55,040 --> 00:25:00,160
Just remember you do not watch 
time-based developments in the same way. 

275
00:25:00,160 --> 00:25:07,040
You watch price-based developments. That might 
mean fewer signals, but they can be clearer.
  

276
00:25:07,040 --> 00:25:13,360
Another variant is a reversal strategy that 
seeks a color shift after a strong run. 

277
00:25:13,360 --> 00:25:18,240
If you see several bricks of the same 
color, and then you get a shift in color,  

278
00:25:18,240 --> 00:25:22,480
that might point to a change.
This is riskier, because you are  

279
00:25:22,480 --> 00:25:26,320
going against the prior momentum.
But if it lines up with a big  

280
00:25:26,320 --> 00:25:32,000
supply or demand zone, it can work.
 
A channel approach can also work. Draw  

281
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:37,920
an upward channel around renko bricks 
that form higher highs and higher lows. 

282
00:25:37,920 --> 00:25:42,480
If price breaks below the channel 
boundary with a red brick, that  

283
00:25:42,480 --> 00:25:47,520
might signal an end to that uptrend.
If you prefer to ride the trend,  

284
00:25:47,520 --> 00:25:52,400
watch the channel lines.
The moment bricks break outside, exit. 

285
00:25:52,400 --> 00:25:56,960
Or you could look for a brand-new 
trade in the other direction. 
  

286
00:25:56,960 --> 00:26:03,440
Price patterns also matter. Head-and-shoulders, 
or double tops or bottoms are easier  

287
00:26:03,440 --> 00:26:08,720
to spot on a renko chart,
Such pattern can signal a turn. 

288
00:26:08,720 --> 00:26:14,880
Look for a neckline. If a new brick closes beyond 
the neckline, that can confirm the pattern. 

289
00:26:18,480 --> 00:26:24,880
Price patterns on renko reduce choppiness.
Now, if you're curious about mastering more  

290
00:26:24,880 --> 00:26:32,320
trading techniques, go ahead and 
watch one of these videos next!

